        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.altdaily.co/email/images/an-dec-16-3.jpg" alt="Cash in money market funds reaches record $6.67 trillion" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Total assets in U.S. money market mutual funds have hit an all-time high of $6.67 trillion, reflecting investor caution despite a 23% rise in the stock market this year. Several factors have contributed to this surge. High stock valuations, with price-to-earnings multiples nearing dot-com bubble levels, have prompted many investors to shift away from equities. Instead, they are opting for the relative safety of money market funds, which currently offer yields around 4.5%, bolstered by strong economic conditions and high interest rates.</p>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
         This trend gained momentum during periods of market uncertainty, such as the pandemic and recent banking crises like the collapse of Silicon Valley Bank. Money market funds have become a popular parking spot for cash as investors seek risk-free returns in an environment of expensive equities. The record inflows suggest a growing preference for safety and liquidity over the potential volatility of riskier investments.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
