          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the Phillips Curve in economics?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.altdaily.co/email/images/an-dec-16-4.jpg" alt="What is the Phillips Curve in economics?" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The Phillips Curve shows the relationship between inflation (how fast prices are rising) and unemployment (the number of people without jobs) in an economy. It suggests that, in the short run, there is a trade-off between the two. When unemployment is low, businesses compete for workers and raise wages, which can lead to higher costs and increased inflation. On the other hand, when unemployment is high, there’s less demand for workers, keeping wages and inflation lower.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          For example, if a country’s economy is booming and most people have jobs, inflation might rise because businesses and consumers are spending more. But if the economy slows down, unemployment increases, and inflation tends to drop.</p>
           <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">However, this relationship doesn’t always hold in the long run, as factors like expectations of inflation or supply shocks (like rising oil prices) can disrupt it. Economists use the Phillips Curve to understand economic trade-offs.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
